name: EXTRA CURRICULAR Issue 13
description:
Extra Curricular is a terrific, content packed mag about folks who get creative in their spare time.

Issue 13 - the Adventure Issue gets off to a great start with adorable cover art by illustrator Sophie Oiseau. 

Inside, clever people featured include the Auckland duo behind POPdining, photographer Gemma Cagnacci, and Melbourne based Sass Cocker of Ask Alice stationery.  

You’ll meet some creatives who manage to keep the dream alive while facing the realities of living out of a suitcase, there is an Explorer’s Guide to give you tips on how to make the most of a big trip overseas, exploring with children, and what to look out for in your own backyard, and the cheat sheet looks at starting your own business. The Martha Goes Green girls are also back with ideas for treats to take on the road.


<font color="#FF3300">AND IF YOU'RE JUST BUYING EXTRA CURRICULAR, IT HAS THE SPECIAL POSTAGE PRICE OF $2.10 WITHIN NZ.</font>

name: EXTRA CURRICULAR Issue 12
description: Was $14.50 Extra Curricular is a terrific, content packed mag about folks who get creative in their spare time. The Tall Tales edition centres around storytelling, with cover art by children's book illustrator Erica Harrison, who is also interviewed in this issue. Issue 12 features three people who have created their own dream day jobs, talks to Sally Greer at Beatnik Publishing, and looks at the work that goes into one of Louise James' hand crafted books. Emma Kidd shows how to make one of her mystical creatures, and Martha Goes Green dish up their version of gingernuts and a cuppa. There are interviews with illustrator Patti Andrews and artist Rachel Walker, and tips from the experts in a cheat-sheet on public speaking. AND IF YOU'RE JUST BUYING EXTRA CURRICULAR, IT HAS THE SPECIAL POSTAGE PRICE OF $2.10 WITHIN NZ.

name: EXTRA CURRICULAR Issue 11
description: Was $14.50 Extra Curricular is a terrific, content packed mag about folks who get creative in their spare time. Issue 11, The Autumn issue, sticks with the theme of 'new beginnings' and is bursting at the seams with great content from the likes of Olivia Coote (who has put together a sweet housewarming gift tutorial), Martha Goes Green (with recipes for a baby shower), and Sonya Nagels (who photographed and interviewed recent returnees to New Zealand, and an amazing converted hotel in Raglan). Pia Jane Bijkerk talks about her new book project and Julia Atkinson of Studio Home chats about her relocation to Auckland. Issue 11 also has the first installment of a new series of cheat-sheets - first up is promotion and marketing. Plus lots more of course! AND IF YOU'RE JUST BUYING EXTRA CURRICULAR, IT HAS THE SPECIAL POSTAGE PRICE OF $2.10 WITHIN NZ.

name: EXTRA CURRICULAR Issue 10
description: Was $14.50 Extra Curricular is a terrific, content packed mag about folks who get creative in their spare time. Issue 10, the summer issue, celebrates our fave little mag reaching double digits. Enclosed is a gorgeous holiday postcard illustrated by Angela Keoghan, and there are great giveaways fromHarvest Textiles, Kester Black, LoveHate and Thunderpants. There are also articles about backyard honeybees and homebrew, sewing, soap-making, and growing your own food. Not to mention recipes to make sourdough, herbal remedies, and ice blocks. You can even create your own little self-sufficient world with a terrarium tutorial. Extra Curricular is printed in full colour with vegetable based inks on 100% recycled stock. AND IF YOU'RE JUST BUYING EXTRA CURRICULAR, IT HAS THE SPECIAL POSTAGE PRICE OF $2.10 WITHIN NZ.

name: THIS IS PARIS by M.Sasek
description: This is Paris was the first of M.Sasek's much loved series of travel books for children (and adults!). Featuring M.Sasek's stunning drawings and witty narrative, This is Paris takes you on a wonderful tour of the sights, people, and even animals, of Paris. This is Paris was first published in 1959, and republished in 2004. The text of the new edition remains the same as the first edition, but includes updated Parisian facts at the end. Miroslav Sasek was born in Prague in 1916. A holiday in Paris inspired him to create children's travel guides.

name: THIS IS THE WAY TO THE MOON by M.Sasek
description: Was $38 In This is the Way to the Moon Sasek takes readers to the space capital of the world, Cape Canaveral, on the Florida coast. He takes a look at rockets, astronauts, launch day, the brains (both human and electronic) behind getting a man to space, plus what's going on outside the NASA fences. Also included are updated statistics about the space programme and the 1969 moon landing. This title was originally published in 1963 as This is Cape Canaveral. Then, when the Cape was renamed after the assassination of President Kennedy, it was published as This is Cape Kennedy. But Cape Kennedy became Cape Canaveral again in 1974, so finally, it was republished in 2009 as This is the Way to the Moon - phew! Miroslav Sasek was born in Prague in 1916. A holiday in Paris inspired him to create children's travel guides, and the first of them, This Is Paris, was published in 1959.
